<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="67" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[264,1325,398,1785]" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,384,398,424]" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[398,629,399,424]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Lithophane" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boogeri">
<emphasis box="[398,629,399,424]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">Lithophane boogeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been confused with 
<taxonomicName authority="Smith" authorityName="Smith" box="[915,1127,399,425]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Lithophane" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longior">
<emphasis box="[915,1032,399,424]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">L. longior</emphasis>
(Smith)
</taxonomicName>
in collections. It is separated from it by the male genitalia: the apex of the valve is broad with a heavy, rugose spinelike process on the ventral margin in 
<taxonomicName box="[846,968,479,504]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Lithophane" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boogeri">
<emphasis box="[846,968,479,504]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">L. boogeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[985,1057,479,505]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1831,1855]" captionTargetBox="[281,1249,485,1814]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[269,1317,468,1824]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4 – 8. Male genitalia of Lithophane species. 4) L. lanei; 5) L. scottae; 6) E. boogeri; 7) L. longior (tip of valve); 8) L. subtilis (tip of valve)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173469/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">
Fig. 
<number box="[1040,1057,479,505]" pageId="6" pageNumber="67" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
), much narrower, with a smaller spine­like process apically and with a ventral lobe in 
<taxonomicName box="[1081,1205,519,544]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Lithophane" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longior">
<emphasis box="[1081,1205,519,544]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">L. longior</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1229,1308,519,545]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1831,1855]" captionTargetBox="[281,1249,485,1814]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[269,1317,468,1824]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4 – 8. Male genitalia of Lithophane species. 4) L. lanei; 5) L. scottae; 6) E. boogeri; 7) L. longior (tip of valve); 8) L. subtilis (tip of valve)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173469/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">
Fig. 
<number box="[1291,1308,519,545]" pageId="6" pageNumber="67" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
). Externally these species are similar with the same range of variation from even gray to mottled gray with fine black etching in the postmedial area. They may also be separated by range: 
<taxonomicName box="[349,475,639,664]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Lithophane" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boogeri">
<emphasis box="[349,475,639,664]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">L. boogeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in association with 
<taxonomicName box="[815,1083,639,664]" class="Pinopsida" family="Cupressaceae" genus="Juniperus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="6" pageNumber="67" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="occidentalis">
<emphasis box="[815,1083,639,664]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">Juniperus occidentalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the western and northwestern Great Basin and 
<taxonomicName box="[626,746,679,704]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Lithophane" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longior">
<emphasis box="[626,746,679,704]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">L. longior</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs from Colorado, south into Arizona, New 
<collectingCountry box="[264,357,719,745]" name="Mexico" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, and western Texas, following the distribution of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Engelm.) Sarg." authorityName="(Engelm.) Sarg." class="Pinopsida" family="Cupressaceae" genus="Juniperus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="6" pageNumber="67" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="monosperma">
<emphasis box="[1036,1323,719,744]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">Juniperus monosperma</emphasis>
(Engelm.) Sarg.
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName box="[471,704,759,784]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Lithophane" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subtilis">
<emphasis box="[471,704,759,784]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">Lithophane subtilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is another juniper feeding species that occurs in southwestern California. The tip of valve is also wide, but unlike 
<emphasis box="[1035,1165,799,824]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">
<taxonomicName box="[1035,1160,799,824]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Lithophane" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boogeri">L. boogeri</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
the digitus is well developed (
<figureCitation box="[458,529,839,865]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1831,1855]" captionTargetBox="[281,1249,485,1814]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[269,1317,468,1824]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4 – 8. Male genitalia of Lithophane species. 4) L. lanei; 5) L. scottae; 6) E. boogeri; 7) L. longior (tip of valve); 8) L. subtilis (tip of valve)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173469/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">
Fig. 
<number box="[513,529,839,865]" pageId="6" pageNumber="67" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="67" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[264,1325,398,1785]" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,457,878,904]" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">Description</emphasis>
. (
<figureCitation box="[483,558,879,905]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStartId="3.[264,382,1563,1587]" captionTargetBox="[276,1292,335,1536]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[269,1317,317,1552]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 3. Adults of Lithophane species. 1 a, b) L. lanei, Ottawa, ON; 2) L. scottae, Ottawa, ON; 3 a, b, c) L. boogeri, nr. Tumalo, OR." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173468/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">
Fig. 
<number box="[542,558,879,905]" pageId="6" pageNumber="67" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
). 
<typeStatus box="[584,698,879,905]" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">Holotype</typeStatus>
: Forewing length 
<quantity box="[920,1009,879,905]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="67" unit="mm" value="20.0">20 mm</quantity>
. Antenna filiform, ciliate; eye orbicular, lashed; head, palpus, prothoracic collar, tufted thorax and tegula gray. Dorsal forewing gray with slightly darker median shade; orbicular and reniform spots obscure, only very slightly lighter gray than rest of wing. Fringe gray. Dorsal hindwing even gray brown with slightly darker discal lunule; fringe pale gray, darker at base. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[394,473,1079,1105]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 – 8" captionStartId="4.[264,382,1831,1855]" captionTargetBox="[281,1249,485,1814]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[269,1317,468,1824]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4 – 8. Male genitalia of Lithophane species. 4) L. lanei; 5) L. scottae; 6) E. boogeri; 7) L. longior (tip of valve); 8) L. subtilis (tip of valve)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173469/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">
Fig. 
<number box="[456,473,1079,1105]" pageId="6" pageNumber="67" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
). Costa of valve broadly sclerotized, becoming broader subapically, narrowing to a rugose, ventrally directed point. Cucullus absent. Digitus vestigial. Fleshy lobe on ventral margin of valve near apex. Clasper arcs upward and then downward to approach dorsal apex of valve. Uncus thickens slightly medially, splayed laterally at apex. Vesica bulbous, bending upward and to the right with two small subapical diverticulae; cornuti absent. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[452,662,1278,1304]" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">Female genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[681,770,1279,1305]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 10" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1554,1578]" captionTargetBox="[369,1287,336,1530]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[269,1317,315,1546]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 10. Female genitalia of Lithophane species. 9) L. lanei; 10) L. boogeri." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173470/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="67">
Fig. 
<number box="[740,770,1279,1305]" pageId="6" pageNumber="67" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
). Ostium bursae heavily sclerotized laterally; ductus bursae with heavily sclerotized ventral plate that twists around to dorsal surface at appendix bursae. Appendix bursae reduced to a swelling at base of ductus seminalis. Bursa bean­shaped, signa absent. Ovipositor lobes with fine setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
